The house in bones still fascinates after 100 years. Take a look at Gaudi's interiors.
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric saury, the staircase with a dinosaur spine and the balconies with open fish mouths.
This is the house Casa Battlo in Barcelona by the architect Antoni Gaudi.
Due to its organic shapes, the house has been given the nickname of House in bones from the locals.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stones, fragments of tiles and mosaics, facade reminiscent of scales and everywhere present of curves, this is all that is typical for Antoni Gaudi’s New Art.
The front facade of the house unfolds its dream lines, its pleasant colors and textures that remind nature and animals.
In a more detailed observation, we see the geometry, the rhythm and the order of thought with precision.
At night the facade of the house becomes even more dramatic and is lit in such a way that the colors feel brighter.
The winding and torsion of the shapes also appears in the interiors with the same measure.
The wood vaguely copies the window frames, balustrades, decorative elements of the doors, the eyebrow and the lamellae.
The Battlo house, which stands in the Eixample district in the shopping street Passeig de Gracia at number 43, was born from the construction of a house in 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
The reconstruction took place for two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, Joseph Battlo, a wealthy entrepreneur, first insisted on the demolition of the old construction and the construction of another all-new but quickly accepted Gaudí’s idea of an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
But the idea of Casa Battlo as a multi-family house was not thought of by Gaudí alone.
The architect Josep Maria Jujol worked with him.
It is precisely on his project that the decorations for an apartment representing the owner of the building and the use of mosaic for the façade were born.
For the façade also worked other artists and creators.
The joint work on Casa Battlo’s plans began with a successful cooperation between Jujol and Gaudi.
Jujol participated in the construction of Gaudi Casa Mila’s house and Guell Park in which there are other works by Gaudi.
The locals named the house hot just after it was finished because of its organic forms "the House in bones".
Others, given the specific mechanism of opening the windows, called it "the house that burns".
It is said that on top of the construction there is a sword similar to that of St. George the patron of Catalonia.
Other sculpture elements of the construction contain hidden religious motifs.
Gaudi thought for the house a unique system in its central heating time, with ventilation vents and typical fireplaces.
Their inclination of 45 degrees seems strange.
During the creation Gaudi absolutely did not adhere to the construction guidelines of the time and did not allow themselves to be hindered by them.
At the beginning of the construction, he obtained the city's building permit, knowing, of course, that the data on the reconstruction plans were so vague that two years later the municipal council was horrified during the completion and demanded modifications.
For example, the members of the municipal council did not like that the building pillars were imposing on the public pavement.
There was never any modification, but, on the contrary, only 15 days after the call of the city Josep Battlo requested (and obtained satisfaction) permission to rent the two highest floors.
The owner moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a common living room and in the third a bedroom and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey house is shared by a staircase through which you can access to an independent roof terrace.
All right angles and straight lines were cancelled by the basic elements of the reconstruction and replaced by curved walls.
Gaudi also worked on the modern concept of connecting spaces.
The common part can be completely connected by opening the doors of the living room and the high society can communicate comfortably or limit private space for more intimate interviews.
The house with Gaudi's reconstruction received in addition to new facades a non-traditional roof and two additional floors.
Gaudi’s play with the light is also impressive, with blue and white glass tiles decorated with the courtyard and with the light wells.
The two-color game gives maximum light in all floors of the house.
Just bet on the principle that white reflects more than dark that, on the contrary, absorbs the rays of the sun.
The Casa Battlo house that was registered in 2005 in the UNESCO World Heritage Fund may be visited by everyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and splendid apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to take this step in 2002 on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
They continued the visits because they found it to be a lucrative business and they expanded the field of visits to the common areas and the ground floor including the roof terraces.
The entrance ticket to the monument is really cheap and costs <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>16.50; students, retirees, groups and tourist card holders have 20 percent discount.
The sum is still above the entrance price to Gaudi’s other buildings in the city.
If you want to feel the real atmosphere of the house with its fantastic towers, you must quickly find a comrade among the inhabitants of the building and visit the house completely.
