Devices to track people are increasingly being asked by parents who want to monitor their children.
Fear for their child leads more and more people to think about monitoring them through a GPS.
The system, put in place at the beginning to search for cars can also be used to track the movement of people and help in some cases such as that of the little Anicka Janatkova.
The instrument is currently as big as a lighter box but will soon be the size of a watch.
The case of little Anicka has evoked a large number of people and they have begun to look for ways to better protect their children.
Even if the price is to disturb their privacy.
“We strive to tell everyone that this is not espionage but just another way to reduce the likelihood of another tragedy,” says Petr Pilin of the company MAcro Weil, one of the suppliers of tracking devices in the Czech market.
"I admit that there may be cases of misuse of such devices, such as putting it in the bag of someone who is not aware of it, but I have not yet encountered such cases."
“Most people are customers who actually buy the product for security reasons,” adds Pilin.
According to him, children should always know for what purposes the "box" is used and how to use it in case of an emergency.
Children's psychologist Dana Bockova draws attention that if the child does not want to wear something like this on him, he will get rid of it.
“And even the smallest ones can show great creativity when it comes to getting rid of something when they don’t want to be under control.”
“Mobile phones, which can cut off like these tracking devices, have already led parents to long waits,” says Bockova.
According to her, the fact that this type of device can help in the event of aggression is very controversial.
"If it's a ready-made kidnapping, the author will do everything possible to ensure that the child doesn't have an electronic device that can locate it."
“Currently, it’s the phone.”
“As soon as the tracking devices develop, they (the criminals) will be looking for them as well because the sale will be supported by an advertising campaign.”
“In such cases, criminals will always be ahead of the police,” the psychologist says.
She still admits that such devices can help in an unprepared aggression by a pedophile.
According to Robert Cech of RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both cars and people, it claims that having this type of device can help, even if it is destroyed in the event of aggression.
"The device can be set in such a way that it is in regular broadcast after a certain period of time."
"In the event that the device is destroyed, it remains the last position of the person concerned."
"The more expensive devices also have an inclinometer that immediately signals the position of the person who slipped and found himself in the elongated position without moving," says Cech.
According to him, so-called smartphones that are equipped with a navigation system, can offer a comparable service after having formatted it with a special prologue.
The problem with the current tracking systems is that it is either a device similar to those that are carried in pendants the size of a lighter box or to the smallest phone devices.
We can always lose them.
According to Pilina of the company Macro Weil, that is why tests are currently being carried out to make devices that look like common digital watches.
"This will have the advantage that the potential aggressor will not be able to recognize the tracking device."
"Or he will realize it after a while, which will have given the police a little more time," he added.
Whether the tracking device is developed in the form of a bracelet or pendant, it will always use the same technology as to track cars.
It is a combination of position acquisition systems using GPS (used commonly in self-navigation) and a cell phone function that alerts the current position of a vehicle.
