A longer index than the annular is a sign of low risk of cancer
Men who have the index longer than the annular are at a lower risk of having prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday by the British magazine Cancer.
This can depend on the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our findings show that the relative finger length serves as a simple test of prostate cancer risk, especially for men before 60 years," said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could thus help determine which men should undergo the prostate cancer test, particularly by combining with genetic risk or other aggravating factors such as family health history, Eeles added.
During the period 1994-2009, she followed with her colleagues in the UK more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time nearly 3,000 healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had the index of the right hand shorter than the annular.
For them as for the 19 percent of those who had the same length of fingers, the same probability of prostate cancer was found.
In the case of those who had the index longer than the annular risk, however, fell to 33 percent, for men before the age of 60 the risk decreased to 87 percent.
The length ratio of the two fingers cited - formed during the prenatal period - indicates in particular the different levels of sexual hormones to which the child is exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index.
Previous research has shown that it is just testosterone that helps in the development of prostate cancer.
Prof. Vacla Paces, a renowned Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, told CTK that he is aware of the study, but it does not appear to him that the relationship between finger length and cancer is “completely demonstrated.”
