Arsenic-tolerant microbe raises the possibility of new types of life on Earth, or elsewhere.
The discovery of a strange bacteria, which can use arsenic as one of its nutrients, expands the field to find new life forms on Earth and perhaps beyond.
Although researchers have discovered the unusual bacteria here on Earth, they say that it shows that life has possibilities beyond the major elements that have been considered essential.
"This body has a double capacity."
"It can develop either with phosphorus or with arsenic."
"That's why it's very special, even though it's far from being a really "foreign" form of life," said Paul Davies C. W. of Arizona State University, co-author of the report appearing in Thursday's online edition of the journal Science.
Six major elements have long been considered essential for life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
But the researchers found that the bacteria, discovered in Lake Mono, California, is able to continue to develop after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
“We wonder what is still possible,” said Ariel Anbar D. of Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
The discovery is important in researching life beyond Earth because researchers need to be able to recognize life, to know what life looks like, says Anbar.
The study focuses on a microbe found on Earth.
However, the announcement of a press conference to discuss it, which did not disclose the details of the finding, generated widespread speculation on the Internet that the report could reveal the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
That was not the case.
The discovery "shows that, in other planetary environments, organisms could be able to use other elements to act on biochemistry and that the "standard" set of elements, which we deem absolutely necessary for life, could not be fixed," said Charles Cockell, open-planetist and professor at the University of Milestitche.
Cockell was not part of the research team.
“This work is new because it shows the substitution of one element to another in fundamental biochemistry and the biochemical structure,” Cockell added.
It was not a casual discovery.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's Institute of Astrology, who led the study, chose Lake Mono because it is equipped with high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar; thus, it speculated that a microbe exposed to the two substances might be able to replace one another.
“Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is really similar to that of phosphorus.”
"As a result, organizations find it difficult to distinguish these elements separately."
“But arsenic is different enough that it doesn’t work exactly like phosphorus; it penetrates inside and somehow rubberizes the work of our biochemical machine,” Anbar explained.
The researchers collected the bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposed it to increasing concentrations of arsenic to which it was able to adapt and grow.
The microbe grows better with phosphorus but the fact that it can live with arsenic instead raises the possibility that a form of life using arsenic can occur naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or the moon where arsenic is more frequent.
Jamie S. Foster, an assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said the idea that arsenic could be replaced by phosphorus was not new; but nothing has ever shown that it could work.
Arsenic was more common at the beginning of the Earth’s existence, she says; thus, researchers have hypothesized that the first forms of life could have used it.
This suggests there may be other ways of forming life, not just the way life on Earth was formed at the beginning," said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was funded by NASA, the Ministry of Energy and the National Institute of Health.
