Can civilization bring the clutches closer?
After a campaign marked by invective and negativity, a minimum of civilization broke out in Washington this week.
Is this a sign of genuine bipartisan cooperation forward or an illusory moment before the rapid return to the partisan struggle in the capital?
The Tuesday meeting between President Obama and Congress leaders did not produce any breakthroughs on the major issues that must be dealt with during the session of the “boxing duck”.
But obviously, there has been at least a polite discussion about the differences between the two parties as well as the recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another episode where each camp wanted to score points.
The president's public meeting on Wednesday's deficit committee was equally civilized, despite the political divergences that remain between the members.
It seems clear that the close interaction of several months has created mutual respect beyond the ideological gap; but which, however, still divides the members.
It is hardly enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
The two sides are now in a period of trial and mutual testing in order to obtain signs of cooperation and compromise, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and electorate patience for a renewed partisan war.
That is why the Tuesday meeting and subsequent comments of the participants revealed a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and Republicans are too large and too deep to suggest a rapid climate change that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it is taxation, expenses, health care or rights, both parties remain miles away.
However, the November election had moderated Washington, at least in the short term.
“There is no doubt that things have changed in the tone,” said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official, now next to the Center for Ethical and Public Policy.
“This is inevitable after the election.
Elections arouse partisan passions and then they fade away.
That's good."
On certain issues, including those on the agenda of the session of the "cowardly duck", Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush’s tax cuts will expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favour of it.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve a part or the whole of it, either permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, a compromise is envisaged on extending unemployment benefits, only because Republicans cannot afford to give the impression that they are in favour of tax cuts for the rich, while refusing unemployment benefits to unemployed workers.
After Tuesday’s meeting at the White House, more optimism is set for a possible agreement on the issues raised during the session on the “cowardly duck”, with the ratification of the “New START” pact.
But William Galston, of the Brookings Institution, warns that successful cooperation on the most pressing issues of the “lame duck” session will not necessarily merge with a better understanding between the two parties when the 112th Congress meets in January.
Instead, he says, a period of disagreement is likely, or even inevitable.
"Once the things that have to be done will be done, psychology in the short term will come back to one of the confrontations," he said.
Wehner also expressed his widely shared skepticism that civilization would lead to true cooperation.
"I consider most of what's happening between today and 2012 as a pre-show or a shadow-boxing compared to the main event in 2012," he said.
The reasons for this are closely linked to the composition of the new Republican majority in the House and to the voters present at the tea that contributed to its creation.
However, Republican leaders are aware of the dangers if they go too far, they know that they must try to keep up with their promises to reduce public spending and repeal the new Healthcare Act.
These supportive positions are already clear in the first reactions to the recommendations of the deficit committee, which include reforming the tax code and increasing certain taxes, delaying the retirement age and reducing spending.
Co-Presidents Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles chose one of the most difficult tasks in Washington and, in their opinion, imposed the issue of the deficit on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they needed 14 votes on the 18-member committee to issue their plan as an official recommendation, and they had difficulty reaching that number.
The strongest resistance remains among the group's elected representatives, suggesting that there is at least today little reason or willingness to compromise on tax issues.
Galston envisages two phases in the battles between the White House and the Republicans of Congress.
The first will come next year in the form of partisan clashes, as Republicans challenge Obama in terms of budget, taxes and health care; followed by a period of greater bilateral cooperation.
What would be the cause of the change?
The public opinion.
It is widely proven that, despite the supportive spirit of the recent election, a majority of Americans always want to see both parties work together.
If the confrontation leads to an impasse, as in 1995, then the two parties will closely observe the reaction of the public.
The one who is judged to lose will have to change his mind and find compromises.
But that would still be an optimistic point of view.
The partisan spirit and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid-1990s and there seems to be a greater ideological gap between Obama and Congress Republicans than there was then between President Bill Clinton and Republicans.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as a simple prelude to a more consecutive election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civilization exposed this week could be appreciated by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort from both sides to find a ground of agreement on the issues that still divide them.
