The second blow to the Central European country was when Merkel had hardly extended the decision to save Greece.
Since then, it has been the subject of fierce criticism, but the truth is that political consensus in Germany and public and public opinion were against the rescue of Greece.
Finally, by the end of October, Merkel again expressed a clear position, calling for the reform of the EU treaties to make it possible to rescue a country and at the same time oblige private lenders to bear a part of the cost.
This position was interpreted as anti-European, as it precipitated the Irish crisis and the rest.
But his proposal, although somewhat sweetened, has been approved and, in the months that follow, we should be assisting in the process of reform of the Union that makes these measures possible from 2013 onwards.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
And she tells us all that, even if we now have to take measures with which we may not agree too much, from that date onwards the old functioning of the euro would have ended.
2013 will mean the birth of a new monetary zone, in which countries that violate the rules will be severely sanctioned, they may be obliged to declare discontinuation of payments, and in that case the private sector will also bear a part of the costs.
Germany signals us that we must follow a strict path of growth with high rates of savings and investment, moderation in consumption, improvements in productivity and competitiveness and positive external balances.
An alternative based on debt and construction, with huge holes in the balance of payments, like the one that presided over Spanish growth in the years of the boom, will simply not be tolerated.
The bet is clear.
And it would be hard not to hear it.
It is not just about bringing the public deficit back to 3% in 2013.
What we are asked for is much harder.
And what he should absolutely not do in these circumstances is to deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will bring us greater tranquility.
And let us know the opportunity we were given, until the spring of 2013.
It seems that President Zapatero has also heard of this form and his double statement (the reforms promised after Saturday's meeting with the big companies and yesterday's announcement of new measures) suggests that, despite Merkel's criticism, we have opened the way for the thesis to be put in place.
But the red line that Germany has drawn is there, and they don’t seem to move it.
And among the possibilities envisaged, one cannot exclude the possibility of abandoning a monetary zone too crowded by less serious countries.
And in that case, Germany will always be able to tell us that it had warned us.
