The European Union changes the rules for obtaining a visa
People must go to the Visa Applicants Service Centers before their interview in the Consular Section; the waiting time will be reduced.
As of January 10, 2011, the visa processing procedure at the U.S. Embassy and Consulate will change.
With the new procedure, the majority of applicants will be required to submit to the Visa Applicants Service Centres (ASC) prior to their interview in the Consular Section.
ASC staff will take biometric information from the applicant, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will present some benefits for aspirants, including the following:
The total cost to process the visa will be lower, no longer will it be necessary to make a payment to get an appointment, another payment for the visa processing and another for the postal service to deliver the document.
The applicant will make a single payment that will cover all three services.
The current rate will remain the same: the equivalent of <0x24>140 for a tourist visa, <0x24>150 for visa applications (including visas for temporary workers) and <0x24>390 for trader and investor visas.
People who wish to renew their visa will not have to submit to an interview with the Consular Representative, they will only appear at the nearest ASC where they will present the documents and their fingerprints will be taken.
Due to the fact that biometric information will be taken in the CSA, applicants who wish to have a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will stay there less time than before.
Similarly, visa applicants to the Consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra <0x24>26 service fee.
For more information on the new visa application procedure, visit the following page http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
